<div id="main_content">
	<h2>Study Praises Baseball for Minority Hiring; Shows Need for More Gender Diversity</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Chad Binette
		
		<span class="date">April 20, 2006</span></p>
	
	
	
		<div class="article_img" style="width: px;">

			<img alt="Article Main Picture" src="../resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/0/NE531/en_US/mannycrop.jpg" height="" width=""  /> 
			
				<p class="photo_credit">Photo: Michael Binette/Sports Pics</p>
			
			<p>The Institute for Diversity and Ethics in Sport's report card gave baseball an 'A' grade for opportunities it gives minorities as players. Manny Ramirez (left) and David Ortiz are two of top players for the Boston Red Sox.</p>
			
				<p class="note"><a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=002400410774959e30109f4453599006cd1">Full Photo</a></p>
			
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
		</div>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:jbartter@bus.ucf.edu ">Jessica Bartter</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-4884</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.ncasports.org/press_releases.htm">Full report card on baseball</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.bus.ucf.edu/sport/cgi-bin/site/sitew.cgi?page=/ides/index.htx">Institute for Diversity and Ethics in Sport</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>Major League Baseball excels at giving minorities opportunities as players, coaches and managers but not as general managers, according to a new report by the <place /><placetype />University</placetype /> of <placename />Central Florida</placename /></place />s Institute for Diversity and Ethics in Sport. </p><p>The report by institute director Richard Lapchick also concluded that Major League Baseball needs to give women more opportunities at the managerial and executive levels. </p><p>Overall, Major League Baseball received a B-plus for race and a D-plus for gender in the report card, which was released Thursday. </p><p>The 2005 season ended with a seeming home run for those urging more open hiring practices with the World Series triumph of the Chicago White Sox, Lapchick wrote in the study. It was the first time a team won the series with a person of color in both positions of manager (Ozzie Guillen) and general manager (Ken Williams). </p><p>However, the percentage of African-American players in baseball last year dropped to 8.5, the lowest it has been since the report cards were first issued in the 1980s. Sixty percent of players in 2005 were white, 29 percent were Latino and 2.5 percent were Asian. </p><p>The reports findings show that among the 30 teams in Major League Baseball, only one majority owner  Arturo Moreno of the Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim  is Hispanic and none are African-American. </p><p>Five of the 30 managers in baseball and 29 percent of the coaches were either African-American or Hispanic. Among senior administrators in Major League Baseballs central office, 24 percent of employees were minorities and 26 percent were women. </p><p>UCFs Institute for Diversity and Ethics in Sport publishes Racial and Gender Report Cards for all major sports. The institute strives to call attention to areas where improvements have been made and to help bring more diversity to areas where it is needed.</p><p>To view the full report on baseball, go to <a href="http://www.ncasports.org/press_releases.htm">www.ncasports.org/press_releases.htm</a>. For more information on the institute, go to <a href="http://www.bus.ucf.edu/sport/cgi-bin/site/sitew.cgi?page=/ides/index.htx">http://www.bus.ucf.edu/sport/cgi-bin/site/sitew.cgi?page=/ides/index.htx</a>.</p>
		
	
	<p id="back"><a href="index?page=news">&lt; Back to the Newsroom</a></p>

